---

# Stepper Compound Component — Implementation Plan

## Overview

The Stepper is a custom compound component with no external primitive dependency. It uses a two-level React context hierarchy, supports controlled/uncontrolled state, and renders in both horizontal and vertical orientations. The pattern mirrors the Carousel component (context + hook pattern) and the typing approach matches Tabs.

Four files must be created, and four registry files must be edited.

---

## File 1: `apps/v4/registry/bases/base/ui/stepper.tsx`

This is the authoritative source. The radix variant (File 2) is a copy with one import path change.

### Design Decisions

**Context hierarchy:**

- `StepperContext` is created with `null` as default and carries `{ value, onValueChange, orientation }`. The `useStepperContext()` hook throws if used outside `<Stepper />`.
- `StepperItemContext` is created with `null` as default and carries `{ value, isActive, disabled }`. The `useStepperItemContext()` hook throws if used outside `<StepperItem />`.

**Controlled vs uncontrolled state:**

`Stepper` accepts `value`, `onValueChange`, and `defaultValue`. This is done by maintaining an internal `React.useState(defaultValue ?? "")` and a separate `React.useRef` to track whether the component is controlled (i.e., `value` prop was provided). The canonical pattern used elsewhere in this codebase is simpler: just merge them. The cleaner approach that fits this library's style is:

```typescript
const [internalValue, setInternalValue] = React.useState(defaultValue ?? "")
const isControlled = value !== undefined
const activeValue = isControlled ? value! : internalValue

function handleValueChange(next: string) {
  if (!isControlled) setInternalValue(next)
  onValueChange?.(next)
}
```

**`StepperContent` rendering:**

Reads `isActive` from `StepperItemContext` and renders `null` when not active. This avoids any hidden/show toggling — the panel simply unmounts. This is the correct default for a wizard/onboarding flow (no stale form state, clean mounting).

**`StepperSeparator` orientation:**

Reads `orientation` from `StepperContext` and applies different CSS depending on it.

**`data-slot` attributes:**

Every element gets `data-slot="stepper"`, `data-slot="stepper-item"`, etc.

**`data-active` attribute:**

`StepperItem` passes `data-active={isActive || undefined}` so CSS can target it. The `|| undefined` pattern removes the attribute entirely when false, which is idiomatic in this codebase (e.g., Tabs uses `data-active` on the trigger via the primitive).

**`data-disabled` attribute:**

`StepperItem` passes `data-disabled={disabled || undefined}`.

**`data-orientation` attribute:**

`Stepper` passes `data-orientation={orientation}`.

### Complete Component Code

```tsx
"use client"

import * as React from "react"

import { cn } from "@/registry/bases/base/lib/utils"

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Root context
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

type StepperContextProps = {
  value: string
  onValueChange: (value: string) => void
  orientation: "horizontal" | "vertical"
}

const StepperContext = React.createContext<StepperContextProps | null>(null)

function useStepper() {
  const context = React.useContext(StepperContext)
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error("useStepper must be used within a <Stepper />")
  }
  return context
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Item context
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

type StepperItemContextProps = {
  value: string
  isActive: boolean
  disabled: boolean
}

const StepperItemContext = React.createContext<StepperItemContextProps | null>(
  null
)

function useStepperItem() {
  const context = React.useContext(StepperItemContext)
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error("useStepperItem must be used within a <StepperItem />")
  }
  return context
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Stepper (root)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

type StepperProps = {
  value?: string
  defaultValue?: string
  onValueChange?: (value: string) => void
  orientation?: "horizontal" | "vertical"
}

function Stepper({
  value,
  defaultValue,
  onValueChange,
  orientation = "horizontal",
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentProps<"div"> & StepperProps) {
  const [internalValue, setInternalValue] = React.useState(defaultValue ?? "")
  const isControlled = value !== undefined
  const activeValue = isControlled ? value! : internalValue

  function handleValueChange(next: string) {
    if (!isControlled) setInternalValue(next)
    onValueChange?.(next)
  }

  return (
    <StepperContext.Provider
      value={{ value: activeValue, onValueChange: handleValueChange, orientation }}
    >
      <div
        data-slot="stepper"
        data-orientation={orientation}
        className={cn(
          "cn-stepper flex",
          orientation === "horizontal" ? "flex-col gap-4" : "flex-col gap-0",
          className
        )}
        {...props}
      >
        {children}
      </div>
    </StepperContext.Provider>
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperItem
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

type StepperItemProps = {
  value: string
  disabled?: boolean
}

function StepperItem({
  value,
  disabled = false,
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentProps<"div"> & StepperItemProps) {
  const { value: activeValue, orientation } = useStepper()
  const isActive = activeValue === value

  return (
    <StepperItemContext.Provider value={{ value, isActive, disabled }}>
      <div
        data-slot="stepper-item"
        data-active={isActive || undefined}
        data-disabled={disabled || undefined}
        className={cn(
          "cn-stepper-item",
          orientation === "vertical" ? "flex flex-row gap-4" : "flex flex-col",
          className
        )}
        {...props}
      >
        {children}
      </div>
    </StepperItemContext.Provider>
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperTrigger
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

function StepperTrigger({
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentProps<"button">) {
  const { onValueChange } = useStepper()
  const { value, isActive, disabled } = useStepperItem()

  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      role="tab"
      data-slot="stepper-trigger"
      data-active={isActive || undefined}
      aria-selected={isActive}
      aria-disabled={disabled || undefined}
      disabled={disabled}
      onClick={() => !disabled && onValueChange(value)}
      className={cn(
        "cn-stepper-trigger inline-flex items-center gap-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperTitle
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

function StepperTitle({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"p">) {
  return (
    <p
      data-slot="stepper-title"
      className={cn("cn-stepper-title text-sm font-medium", className)}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperDescription
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

function StepperDescription({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"p">) {
  return (
    <p
      data-slot="stepper-description"
      className={cn(
        "cn-stepper-description text-sm text-muted-foreground",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperSeparator
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

function StepperSeparator({ className, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<"div">) {
  const { orientation } = useStepper()

  return (
    <div
      data-slot="stepper-separator"
      className={cn(
        "cn-stepper-separator bg-border",
        orientation === "horizontal" ? "h-px flex-1" : "ms-4 w-px self-stretch",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// StepperContent
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

function StepperContent({
  value,
  className,
  children,
  ...props
}: React.ComponentProps<"div"> & { value: string }) {
  const { value: activeValue } = useStepper()

  if (activeValue !== value) return null

  return (
    <div
      data-slot="stepper-content"
      className={cn("cn-stepper-content", className)}
      {...props}
    >
      {children}
    </div>
  )
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Exports
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

export {
  Stepper,
  StepperItem,
  StepperTrigger,
  StepperTitle,
  StepperDescription,
  StepperSeparator,
  StepperContent,
  useStepper,
  useStepperItem,
}
```

---

## File 2: `apps/v4/registry/bases/radix/ui/stepper.tsx`

Identical to File 1 with one change: the `cn` import path.

```diff
-import { cn } from "@/registry/bases/base/lib/utils"
+import { cn } from "@/registry/bases/radix/lib/utils"
```

Everything else — all component code, context creation, logic — is a verbatim copy of File 1. This mirrors exactly how `carousel.tsx` is duplicated between `base/` and `radix/`.

---

## File 3: `apps/v4/registry/bases/base/examples/stepper-example.tsx`

### Design Decisions

- Two variants: horizontal (3-step Account/Profile/Confirm) and vertical (same 3 steps).
- Both use `defaultValue="account"` so no external state is needed. This matches the `"use client"` requirement since the root `Stepper` manages internal state.
- The horizontal variant uses a header row: `flex flex-row items-center` container holding alternating `StepperTrigger` and `StepperSeparator` elements, then `StepperContent` panels below.
- Step indicators (the numbered circles) are rendered by the user inside `StepperTrigger`, not by the component itself.
- Navigation buttons use the existing `Button` component from the same base.
- The example file imports `Button` and uses `useStepper` from the stepper to wire "Next"/"Previous" buttons. However, since `useStepper` is a hook, calling it in the example variant functions would require those functions to be React components (which they already are). The "Next"/"Previous" buttons call `onValueChange` on the next/previous step value. The example hardcodes the step order.

```tsx
"use client"

import {
  Example,
  ExampleWrapper,
} from "@/registry/bases/base/components/example"
import { Button } from "@/registry/bases/base/ui/button"
import {
  Stepper,
  StepperContent,
  StepperDescription,
  StepperItem,
  StepperSeparator,
  StepperTitle,
  StepperTrigger,
  useStepper,
} from "@/registry/bases/base/ui/stepper"

export default function StepperExample() {
  return (
    <ExampleWrapper className="lg:grid-cols-1">
      <StepperHorizontal />
      <StepperVertical />
    </ExampleWrapper>
  )
}

const steps = [
  {
    value: "account",
    title: "Account",
    description: "Set up your account details",
    content: "Enter your name, email, and choose a username for your account.",
  },
  {
    value: "profile",
    title: "Profile",
    description: "Personalize your profile",
    content: "Upload a photo and write a short bio to introduce yourself.",
  },
  {
    value: "confirm",
    title: "Confirm",
    description: "Review and confirm",
    content: "Review your information and confirm to complete setup.",
  },
]

function StepperHorizontal() {
  return (
    <Example title="Horizontal">
      <Stepper defaultValue="account" className="w-full max-w-lg">
        <div className="flex flex-row items-center">
          {steps.map((step, index) => (
            <React.Fragment key={step.value}>
              <StepperItem value={step.value} className="flex-none">
                <StepperTrigger className="flex flex-col items-center gap-1">
                  <span className="flex size-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full border-2 text-sm font-semibold data-active:border-primary data-active:bg-primary data-active:text-primary-foreground">
                    {index + 1}
                  </span>
                  <StepperTitle>{step.title}</StepperTitle>
                </StepperTrigger>
              </StepperItem>
              {index < steps.length - 1 && <StepperSeparator />}
            </React.Fragment>
          ))}
        </div>
        {steps.map((step) => (
          <StepperContent key={step.value} value={step.value}>
            <div className="rounded-lg border p-4">
              <p className="text-sm font-medium">{step.title}</p>
              <p className="mt-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground">{step.content}</p>
              <StepperNavigation steps={steps} currentValue={step.value} />
            </div>
          </StepperContent>
        ))}
      </Stepper>
    </Example>
  )
}

function StepperVertical() {
  return (
    <Example title="Vertical">
      <Stepper defaultValue="account" orientation="vertical" className="w-full max-w-sm">
        {steps.map((step, index) => (
          <React.Fragment key={step.value}>
            <StepperItem value={step.value}>
              <div className="flex flex-col">
                <StepperTrigger className="items-start">
                  <span className="flex size-8 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border-2 text-sm font-semibold data-active:border-primary data-active:bg-primary data-active:text-primary-foreground">
                    {index + 1}
                  </span>
                  <div className="flex flex-col text-left">
                    <StepperTitle>{step.title}</StepperTitle>
                    <StepperDescription>{step.description}</StepperDescription>
                  </div>
                </StepperTrigger>
                <StepperContent value={step.value} className="ms-12 pb-4">
                  <p className="text-sm text-muted-foreground">{step.content}</p>
                  <StepperNavigation steps={steps} currentValue={step.value} />
                </StepperContent>
              </div>
              {index < steps.length - 1 && <StepperSeparator />}
            </StepperItem>
          </React.Fragment>
        ))}
      </Stepper>
    </Example>
  )
}

function StepperNavigation({
  steps,
  currentValue,
}: {
  steps: typeof steps
  currentValue: string
}) {
  const { onValueChange } = useStepper()
  const currentIndex = steps.findIndex((s) => s.value === currentValue)

  return (
    <div className="mt-4 flex gap-2">
      {currentIndex > 0 && (
        <Button
          variant="outline"
          size="sm"
          onClick={() => onValueChange(steps[currentIndex - 1].value)}
        >
          Previous
        </Button>
      )}
      {currentIndex < steps.length - 1 && (
        <Button
          size="sm"
          onClick={() => onValueChange(steps[currentIndex + 1].value)}
        >
          Next
        </Button>
      )}
      {currentIndex === steps.length - 1 && (
        <Button size="sm" onClick={() => onValueChange(steps[0].value)}>
          Restart
        </Button>
      )}
    </div>
  )
}
```

Note: `React.Fragment` requires `import * as React from "react"` at the top of the file. Since example files in this library do not always have that import, use the JSX fragment shorthand `<>...</>` or add the React import. Looking at the examples like `progress-example.tsx`, they do include `import * as React from "react"` when using hooks. Add it here since `useStepper` is used.

The corrected import block for the example:

